atively the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gender </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disparity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">found in employment of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">freelance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">directors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.   The BBC is engaged in discussions with us on a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">number of initiatives to improve the current situation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC has traditionally been slow to adopt </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">certain key </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">industry standard tools and operations, preferring to devise its own bespoke – and often very expensive – alternatives.  One example of this i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s the adoption of ISAN </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> numbers for programmes, which would facilitate worldwide tracking and exploitation of digital content.  Richard Hooper has been pressing the BBC to adopt this, and we fully endorse that ambition.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The BBC’s support for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the UK’s film industry, by way of funding and broadcasting original UK </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">productions is at a low level, especially compared with other major European countries such as France.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2010, UK public investment for the UK film industry totalled £347 million whil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">st in France the combined investment from the CNC Support Fund and mandatory support by French broadcasters totalled £578 million</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:5.33pt; vertical-align:super">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The vast bulk of UK support takes the form of the tax credit.  The BBC’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contribution to film funding is just £12m per year.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We urge the Committee to recommend that the BBC should spend a great deal more on British film funding.  We would also recommend that the BBC should make more provision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for investing in film talent, both through funding and through broadcasting filmed shor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ts, often a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> calling card for emerging film</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">makers.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We welcome the BBC’s recent decision to revise its delivery rules and accept content delivery on super16mm formats for use on their HD output channels.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This decision helps to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">protect </span><span